.The government has been relatively stable in the last two years, but the Prime Minister's age (and duration in office) have brought out the opposition.  The migration/refugee issue (with the accompanying change in tone after the Paris attacks) will add to the current political environment to drive significant flux. The legislature is very representative (1 representative for roughly ten thousand citizens), so individual legislators are inherently much more sensitive to the desires of their constituents.  The demonstrations have been (as of yet) relatively small numerically, but as a percentage of the population it has to be taken into account that it is a very small country.

I knew practically nothing about Montenegro and Djukanovic before rather unnecessarily jumping into the NATO invitation question, but now that I'm in I may as well attempt this one as well. 50 days for this question to resolve. Djukanovic has been either Prime Minister or President for almost all the time since 1991, and having been groomed in Yugoslavia's Communist Party should know very well how to manipulate levers to stay in power, even in what is now a multi-party democratic system. 50 days vs nearly 25 years suggests a base probability of less than 1%. So what has changed? Demonstrations against him and his government, primarily because the likelihood of Montenegro's joining NATO in the near future has increased.  With elections just round the corner next year, why should his opponents want him to resign now? If they win the next election they could withdraw their application to NATO. Perhaps they know they can't win the elections, and are relying on street power and outside help to force him out? Russia is probably too busy elsewhere to send "change agents" to Montenegro in the next few weeks.  I think Djukanovic can ride this out till 01 Jan 2016, whether or not the NATO invitation comes through, and only some "unknown unknown" such as a major personal scandal could change this forecast.

That is, the whole intelligentsia is starting to move away to the other side,” Striga is sure.

COMMENT:  The protests in Oct drew thousands, but not tens of thousands as organizers had predicted and hoped for, and have now fizzled away to almost nothing.  I can imagine that an invitation to join NATO could be very de-stabilizing in Montenegro and eventually lead to Djukanovic's ouster, but this question has a very narrow time-window.  Would sufficient numbers of people be roused to come out to protest in winter, at Christmas?  Why not just wait until the elections?  I just don't see this happening prior to New Years.
Initial forecast - short timeframe, and the demonstrations to date do not seem to be of a level sufficient to cause a change in leadership. Elections are scheduled in any case.

Timescale seems far too short, past precedent lacking, and Djukanovic's power too entrenched and long-term, with no obvious replacement with sufficiently widespread popular support yet evident.  (Protest leaders being relatively second-rank - unlike those who were prominent e.g. before "rose" and "orange" revolutions in Georgia and Ukraine). Not convinced a comparison with pre-2000 Serbia stands either, for several reasons. Broader situation:
Djukanovic has been PM for much of the past 25 years (1991-98, 2003-06, 2008-10, and since 2012). But True, Djukanovic's party , by itself, just lacks a parliamentary majority (39 out of 81 seats at last election - already over 3 years ago, in Oct 2012), and the formal governing majority is narrow (43 seats - the remaining four representing minority ethnic parties - Bosniaks and Croats - that might be expected to be broadly sympathetic to NATO membership - a probable "trigger issue" in the next few weeks). Last presidential election, in 2013, was close, with a member of Djukanovic's party  winning by a very narrow margin (51%-49%) over a candidate from an alliance in which the main "pro-Russian" party, NOVA, was a major constituent element. Counter-arguments: elsewhere in the Balkans (albeit, in both cases, in countries that have rather different political traditions from Montenegro), such resignations HAVE occurred recently in Romania and Moldova (with pro-Russian. elements seemingly involved in the latter case. But Russia's position in Moldova, and the country's geographical situation in Russia's "Near Abroad" - and ex-Soviet connections) are among the things that make that more vulnerable to pressure than is Montenegro.
